The doctrine that time cannot be known apart from motion and rest was worked out ογ Aristotle. Lucr. is in error in denying utterly its objective existence, as he does 459. We reach our conceptione of time and space only through experience ; indeed experience is apprehended by us only in terms‚ as it were, of time and space; but that there is something outside of ourselves cor· responding to these conceptione, few will deny. Lucretius’ error originates in the notion of ‘existence’ held by the Epicureans, Elea· ties, and most ancient philosophers. By them ‘existence ’ was predi· cated either of matter alone, or of matter and spirit, oroi matter and void; but properly speaking the concept covers both substance, phys· ical and spiritual, and relations, as cause and effect, space, time.
